<paper id="1963893098"><title>Developing a long-range information architecture</title><year>1983</year><authors><author org="University Of Minnesota, Minneapolis, Minnesota" id="116766436">James C. Wetherbe</author><author org="University Of Minnesota, Minneapolis, Minnesota" id="2108307508">Gordon B. Davis</author></authors><n_citation>25</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>2066900729</reference><reference>2092632945</reference></references><venue id="2626428507" type="C">National Computer Conference</venue><doi>10.1145/1500676.1500709</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.63">Data architecture</keyword><keyword weight="0.6452">Business system planning</keyword><keyword weight="0.64721">Applications architecture</keyword><keyword weight="0.65697">Enterprise architecture</keyword><keyword weight="0.47782">Software engineering</keyword><keyword weight="0.45678">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.63394">Solution architecture</keyword><keyword weight="0.43454">Real-time computing</keyword><keyword weight="0.63043">Reference architecture</keyword><keyword weight="0.64924">Enterprise architecture framework</keyword><keyword weight="0.62791">Business architecture</keyword><keyword weight="0.48231">Process management</keyword></keywords><publisher>ACM</publisher><abstract>A methodology is presented for eliciting enterprise information requirements and developing a long-range information architecture. The methodology is based on a combination of business system planning, critical success factors, and ends/means analysis. The methodology is independent of organizational structure, personnel, and hardware and software; and it has been successfully implemented in a variety of organizational settings.</abstract></paper>